% income tax --> positive externalities of income taxation
The implementation of the income tax law had positive spillovers on state consolidation. Income taxation was not only important because of the new revenue it collected, but also for state consolidation (\cite[98]{Musgrave1992}, \cite[298]{Moore2004a}). Kaldor points out that the revenue service is the ``point of entry.'' Once this institution is established, the expected marginal cost of improving/implementing other ``state-capacities'' is lower \autocite[15]{Brautigam2008}. In other words, there were \emph{technical complementarities}\footnote{Which are situations in which ``an increase in the output of [a] commodity [...] lowers the marginal costs of producing [other] commodity'' \parencite[67]{Hirschman:1958aa}.} between implementing the income tax, and fostering overall levels of state institutionalization. The literature is consistent in that the \emph{introduction} of the income tax is associated with state expansion. For instance, \textcite[208]{Besley2013a} explain that \emph{implementing} the income tax law is ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection'' in a number of countries, including Chile, while \textcite[3]{Dincecco2015a} find ``a positive and significant relationship between the introduction of the income tax, and (1) per capita total expenditures, (2) per capita education expenditures, and (3) per capita health expenditures.'' In Chile, bureaucrats that were sent to collect and administer taxes eventually learned to solve land disputes and dispense justice, among other state tasks. For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley, and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory. Others have found that literacy levels rose in 1907 from 40\% to 66\% in 1925 (Engerman, Sokoloff and Mariscal, in \cite[ch. 5]{Engerman:2011aa}). The share of national revenue accounted for by income taxes after implementing the income tax in 1924 rose from 6\% in 1920 to 23.7\% in 1940 (Engerman, Sokoloff and Zolt, in \cite[178]{Engerman:2011aa}). Humud (1969, p. 154) documents that the income tax was widely enforced, generating considerable resources for the Chilean treasury (in \cite[451-452]{Bowman1982}). The dependence on custom taxes decreased from 70.2\% to 41.1\% during those same years (Engerman, Sokoloff and Zolt, in \cite[ch. 6]{Engerman:2011aa}). Finally, I find in a different project that the income tax in Chile produced state-capacities over time \parencite{Bahamonde:2017ac}. All these developments suggest that policies that expanded the reach of the state increased considerably \emph{after} implementing the income tax.





\section{The Timing of the Implementation of the Income Tax: Late and Early Implementers}

% When
\hypertarget{when}{\emph{When} countries implement the income tax is a substantively important quantity of interest}. Income taxation should have positive spillover effects on state development only if its implementation is situated during the formative years of the polity. Early implementers should have persistent comparative advantages through learning-by-doing, and agglomeration effects. Otherwise, once other major institutions are set in place (and once there is a clear set of winners and losers), even if some kind of direct taxation is (belatedly) imposed, it should be very costly to alter the underlying incentives of that particular institutional order. Since late implementers had lower levels of sectoral conflict---too low to trigger a critical juncture---they kept reproducing the legacies of the post-colonial backwards institutions.


While all countries in the region eventually implemented some system of direct taxation (see \autoref{fig:incometax}), the  process late implementers went through did not reflect the domestic sectoral dynamics explained in this paper, but other forces. While early implementers consolidated the state \emph{in light} of taxation, late implementers evolved \emph{despite} taxation. Moreover, implementing the income tax in contexts where the post-colonial agricultural economic elites were still the ruling political elites represents a missed opportunity to transform the state. In fact, I find somewhere else that in a number of Latin American countries that, when the income tax is adopted under contexts of sectoral contestation, economic growth is more likely to be sustained in the long run \parencite{Bahamonde:2017aa}. 

%In this paper I focus on how different levels of sectoral contestation delayed/accelerated the timing of the implementation of the tax, compromising/fostering state making.




%
The political incorporation of industrial elites promoted lower levels of defection. Industrial elites were willing to impose an income tax on their own incomes, in exchange for being able to participate in the political life of the polity. In turn, political incorporation altered the post-colonial (backwards) institutional order by crystallizing a process of state consolidation via the expansion of the fiscal system. This reasoning is in line with \textcite[7]{Beramendi2016} who argue that ``so long as agricultural elites are the dominant political power-holders in society, then fiscal capacity should remain relatively small, because such elites will prefer \emph{not} to invest in greater fiscal capacity.''\footnote{Emphasis in original. See also for a similar approach \textcite{Ansell:2014ty} and \textcite{Collier:2002db}.} 






% Chile and Guatemala
To add some context, a brief example about two divergent cases is presented. Chile imposed the income tax law very early, in $\Sexpr{load("/Users/hectorbahamonde/RU/Dissertation/Papers/IncomeTaxAdoption/incometax_data.RData");min(data$year[data$country=="Chile" & data$incometax.d == 1])}$, and the Chilean \emph{Servicio de Impuestos Internos} is among the finest tax institutions in Latin America (\cite{Bergman2003a}, \cite[38]{Fairfield2010}). Unlike Chile, Guatemala imposed the income tax law very late, in $\Sexpr{load("/Users/hectorbahamonde/RU/Dissertation/Papers/IncomeTaxAdoption/incometax_data.RData");min(data$year[data$country=="Guatemala" & data$incometax.d == 1])}$. By 1967, the national income tax office employed only 194 people, with only 9 of them having a college degree \autocite[5]{DiJohn2006}. In fact, Cabrera and Schneider not only find that ``Guatemala collects among the lowest tax levels in Latin America,'' but also that ``the revenues it does collect are gathered inefficiently'' \autocite[128]{Mahon2014}. That is, while Guatemala did eventually implement income taxation, the persistence of backwards institutions have precluded Guatemala's ability to implement a modern fiscal apparatus. This paper contends that endogenous sectoral conflicts played an important role in explaining fiscal modernization. In this case in particular, non-agricultural elites have not been strong enough to trigger a critical juncture. When these endogenous forces have been weak or inexistent, income taxation was implemented for other reasons, not transforming the state. In fact, the income tax law in Guatemala was implemented exogenously by the US-backed dictator Colonel Enrique Peralta Azurdia, not necessarily reflecting the inter-sectoral domestic dynamics. The next section expands the Chilean case.




