\section{Unpacking the Mechanisms: Chile 1850-1950\label{unpacking}}

% two classes // debate
\paragraph{A two-sector society}\hypertarget{unpacking}{Historians still debate whether agriculturalists and industrialists comprised two \emph{different} elites}. Some claim that this dualism is incorrect \parencite[125]{Mamalakis:1976kx}. They argue that since landowners also invested in industry (\cite[57, 95]{Kirsch:1977aa}, \cite[180]{Bauer:2008kx}, \cite[23]{Coatsworth2002}),\footnote{\textcite[23]{Coatsworth2002}  argue that ``[t]he only landowners that mattered in 19th century Latin American politics were those for whom land represented but one asset in a much broader portfolio.'' Similarlt, \textcite[180]{Bauer:2008kx} argues that ``[m]iners and merchants bought haciendas but landowners in turn invested in banks, insurance companies, commercial firms and the incipient industrial sector.''} there was a blurry class division between the mining, banking, and agricultural sectors \parencite[30, 44, 94, 108]{Bauer:2008kx}. I contend that there is a series of stylized facts that suggests that there was indeed a structural cleavage between the two sectors. 


% practices
However, there were certain practices that masked the sectoral cleavage. For example, it was common that industrialists invested in real estate. However, in many instances they did so \emph{just} to obtain credit. \textcite[59]{Kirsch:1977aa} explains that ``in a \emph{rural society} land offered one of the best guarantees for loans [since] loans could not be secured by equipment, machinery, or inventory. Only real estate was acceptable collateral.''\footnote{Emphases are mine.} In fact, this practice shows how the credit system was oriented to give unfair advantage to the landed elites (\cite[9]{UndaGutierrez2017}, \cite[11]{Mamalakis1969}). Similarly, \textcite[174]{Zeitlin:1984aa} finds that while there were some instances where there were mixed investments, ``the combined ownership of capital and landed property was a distinctive quality of \emph{certain} [elites] actors.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} There were also other instances where miners invested in banking. However, \textcite{Segall1953} argues that Chilean bankers, after the crisis of the mining sector around the 1870s, acquired a number of mineral deposits given as collateral years before, again suggesting that the lack of economic dualism is rather apparent. Similarly, but for the Argentinean case, \textcite[609]{Hora2002} explains that ``the image of an entrepreneurial elite with assets \emph{scattered throughout several spheres of investment} does not appear entirely correct.''\footnote{Emphasis is mine.} 

% granger / Lewis
In addition to that, the nature of the main factors of production of agriculturalists (land), and industrialists (capital), accelerated the sectoral cleavage. Borrowing from the Lewis model of economic growth, I explain elsewhere that there were a number of structural conditions that should have prevented massive cross-sectoral investments \parencite{Bahamonde:2017aa}. Given the transference of labor from agriculture to the industrial sector,\footnote{The industrial sector uses capital and labor with increasing returns to scale, while agriculture uses land (which is fixed) as the main input (\cite[311]{Jorgenson1961}, \cite[59]{Ranis:1964uq}, \cite[291]{Jorgenson1967}, \cite[279-280]{Skott1998}, \cite[290]{Vollrath2009a}).} and given that the agricultural sector is determined to lag behind the industrial sector,\footnote{To clarify, ``the agricultural sector declines relative to the overall economy but continues to expand absolutely'' \parencite[14]{Nerlove1994}. In other words, it is the ``the proportional contribution of agriculture to the growth'' that decays \parencite[45]{Kuznets1961a}, implying that in the long run the agricultural sector ``must also grow'' \parencite[534]{Ranis1961}, especially given the continuing dependence on a constant supply of food \parencite[2]{Nicholls1963}.} elites invested in both sectors should experiment important allocative inefficiencies, and deadweight losses. This puts heavy pressures to invest in one sector, or the other, but not both. Granger-causality tests and VAR models (not shown here) show that in developed Latin American countries, agricultural expansion caused industrial expansion (modern growth). The opposite is true in non-developed Latin American countries: industrial expansion caused agricultural expansion (backwards growth).\footnote{The developed/non-developed typology presented in \textcite[5]{Mahoney:2010aa} was used.}



% two *antagonist* classes
\paragraph{Sectoral Antagonism}In all Latin American economies during, and right after the colonial period, agriculture was the most important sector, economically and politically \autocite[13]{Keller1931}. And by extension, the economic interests of the agricultural elite were the only economic interests represented in politics \parencite[45-46]{Wright1975}.\footnote{\textcite[19]{Mamalakis1969} refers to this period as the \emph{traditional pattern of government-export sector coalition}.} For example, \textcite[106]{Collier:2002db} argue that initially, the ``national government was dominated by the central part of the country, with owners of large agricultural holdings playing a predominant role'' (see also \cite[15]{McBride:1971fv}). Moreover, political institutions, and social norms inherited from the colonial period, were designed to allocate economic inputs (and hence \emph{growth}) in a way that benefited the landowning class only \parencite{Bahamonde:2017aa}. 


However, despite that in some cases a strong industrial sector emerged, their corresponding elites were kept from participating in politics with the same privileges and conditions that the landowning political elites had. Consequently, the opportunity costs of implementing policies designed to enhance the agricultural sector were low. \textcite[13]{Zeitlin:1984aa} argues that ``landowners controlled both the vote and the labor power of the agrarian tenants (\emph{inquilinos}) and dependent peasants (\emph{minifundistas}), and this was the \emph{sine qua non} of their continuing political hegemony.'' In Congress, and the presidency itself, landowners were the single most important group \parencite[45]{Bauer:2008kx}, leaving the modern sector heavily under-represented \parencite[1748]{Baland2008}. Consequently, fiscal pressures in favor of agricultural taxes were minimal compared with mining taxes,\footnote{Mining was one of the first manifestations of industrial activity. For example,  while an agricultural income tax was imposed, it was weak and abolished after the civil war of 1891.} leaving the agricultural sector systematically---and substantially---undertaxed relative to other sectors \autocite[56]{Best1976}.\footnote{\textcite[81]{Bauer:2008kx} provides a very plausible explanation for why the agricultural sector was ``structurally'' protected against taxation. As he explains, ``[t]he availability of an easily accountable source of public revenue---bags of nitrate or bars of cooper---meant that any need for the Chilean government to intrude into the affairs of landowners was reduced [...] the state kept its political hands off the countryside until the overwhelming urban demands for more food and political support in the 1960s.'' \textcite[38]{Zeitlin:1984aa} also points out that ``public revenues came almost exclusively from taxes on mining and its exports.''} \textcite[118]{Bauer:2008kx} explain that ``[i]n those areas where the government did interfere in the countryside, the effect was to strengthen the position of the landowning class.'' For example, the little public infrastructure that existed, mostly benefited the agricultural sector \parencite{Rippy:1971rz,Marichal:1989bh,Zeitlin:1984aa,Bauer:2008kx}.


% Inter-class inequality and inter-class conflicts // Political bargains
This asymmetry led these two ``antagonistic elites'' \parencite[37-38]{Keller1931} to confront in the civil wars of 1851-1859 and 1891, between a ``large landed property [elite against a] productive capital [elite]'' \parencite[23]{Zeitlin:1984aa}. President Balmaceda's overthrowing explains the sectoral nature of these conflicts. On the one hand, he was mainly supported by the landed elites, but later overthrown in 1891 by a mainly industrial/mining coalition \parencite[186]{Zeitlin:1984aa}. While his agenda on ``industrial'' infrastructure (mainly roads and railroads) benefited mostly agricultural areas \autocite[124]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, his attitude towards the banking sector---closely linked to the mining sector, \cite[118]{Zeitlin:1984aa}---was ``all but confiscatory'' \parencite[175]{Zeitlin:1984aa}. On the other hand, however, he failed to secure a coalition with his own sector. \textcite[127]{Zeitlin:1984aa} explains that the ``decline of wheat exports [...] came precisely when a vast new market for agriculture was growing in the nitrate territory.'' As the agricultural sector supplied the industrial areas with foodstuff, it simultaneously increased the sectoral dependence of the agricultural elites on the industrial sector, forcing the ``landed proprietors [to] become dependent to a considerable extent on the continuing prosperity of the major nitrate capitalists'' \autocite[129]{Zeitlin:1984aa}. While it would be inaccurate to say that Balmaceda was \emph{completely} supported by agriculturalists, and \emph{completely} opposed by industrialists, this example illustrates how a failed inter-sectoral alliance, and a biased strategy regarding the provision of public goods against industrialists led these two groups to a series of military conflicts. 


However, lower levels of inter-elite inequality gave both elites access to similar military resources, preventing subsequent conflicts. While \emph{Balmacedistas} managed to secure the support of the army, \emph{congresistas} (the anti-Balmaceda group) managed to gather support of the navy \parencite[176]{Leonard:2013aa}. Ultimately, the conflict left a permanent scar in the Chilean society. While the civil war lasted only nine months, it took 10,000 lives (out of a total population of 3 million people), and cost more than \$100 million \autocite[86]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, a significant amount for a small country. This legacy materialized in an inefficient, but politically stable system for several years. In part, the immobilism was due to the fact that the political reforms that gave way to the ``parliamentary'' period came out from inter-elite alliances \parencite[108]{Collier:2002db}. However, the intention to avoid more violence (at least among the elites) tended to persist. For instance, while all ``ministers, counselors of state, members of the constituent congress [,] municipal officials, provincial governors and intendants, members of the judiciary and even the lowest functionaries and ordinary employees of Balmaceda's government were investigated [or] brought to trial'' \parencite[87]{Zeitlin:1984aa}, there were a number of amnesties issued. Similarly, there were a number of \emph{aborted} coups in 1907, 1912, 1915 and 1919 \parencite[109]{Collier:2002db}. All in all, there seemed to be a clear avoidance of more conflict.\footnote{Similarly, \textcite{Geddes1991} argues that competition between two rival parties of about the same size creates clearer incentives to invest in political institutions.} 


Under such circumstances, there were heavier pressures for a sectoral compromise. Three institutional components were considered: an income tax, industrial protectionism, and equal access to the state.\footnote{The SOFOFA pursued a very strong protectionist agenda. \textcite[122]{Sokoloff2007a} explain that the expansion of ``manufacturing production [...] helped to nurture the development of a powerful constituency for higher tariffs.''} In fact, \textcite[53]{Lederman2005} and \textcite[18]{Haber2005} find that in Chile, the timing of protectionist and income taxation cycles matches. 



%Importantly, the faster the industrial growth, the higher the pressures to impose a tax to capture increasing industrial incomes.\footnote{\textcite[59]{Besley:2011aa}, \textcite{Beramendi2016}.}



\paragraph{Implementing the Income Tax} The income tax law was passed in Chile in the middle of big political instability. In 1920, President Alessandri obtained a very close victory against Luis Barros Borgo\~no \parencite[111]{Collier:1999rz}, who was supported by ``the dominant political and landed aristocracy'' \autocite[2]{Haring1931}. Governability was seriously compromised as the election left the senate in control of the landowning class, who roundly opposed tax reforms \autocite[5]{Haring1931}. Particularly, the opposition had ``serious differences [...] over [Alessandri's] legislative program, especially in connection with the proposed income tax'' \autocite[3]{Haring1931}. In 1924, the income tax law was passed. As others explain, the non-agricultural ``accepted taxation, \emph{while demanding state services and expecting to influence how tax revenues were spent}'' (Carmenza Gallo, in \cite[165]{Brautigam2008}).\footnote{Emphases are mine. She refers specifically to the mining elites.} The law taxed 2\% on professional income above 2,400 pesos, 3.5\% on net profits in industry and commerce above the same sum, 5\% on income from mining, and 9\% per cent on incomes from real estate \autocite[552]{James1924}. Humud (1969, p. 154) explains that in ``1930 [the tax] would become second only to import duties in size'' \parencite[451-452]{Bowman1982}. %In turn, the military was concerned with the general budget situation. Salaries of army and navy officers ``were two months in arrears.''\footnote{\textcite[6]{Haring1931}.} Famously, on September 3 of 1924 young officials attended the galleries of the senate, and made noise with their sabers to demonstrate their discontent. After the resignation of the entire cabinet, president Alessandri sided with the army in an effort to accelerate the implementation of several pieces of legislation that have been blocked by congress for months. 


% The implementation of the income tax in Chile was associated with the implementation of other state institutions, expanding the bureaucratic \emph{dominion} of the state. However, unlike other ``regular'' state institutions and services, taxing incomes infiltrated the state's coercive sovereignty unto the individual itself. It was the practice of this technology that gave the state the big push allowing the reproduction of its power in other areas throughout the territory. Following the fiscal sociology paradigm, I contend that the more effectively the state taxed its subjects, the more knowledge accumulated performing \emph{other} state activities. The knowledge and expertise the state accumulated were transfered to other state institutions via spillovers, augmenting the overall levels of \emph{stateness}. For instance, it was necessary to send official emissaries to check on accounting books of the refinery in the north, the winery in the central valley and the \emph{hacienda} in the south. Eventually, these delegations became more complex, increasing the density of state presence in the territory. For instance, \textcite{Strayer:2005uq} explains how official state delegations traveled the territory dispensing judicial decisions, fostering state centralization. \textcite{Besley2013a} explain that implementing the income tax law is ``associated with investments in public administrative structures that support tax collection.'' For instance \textcite{Bahamonde:2017ac} finds that fiscal effectiveness can be explained in that (1) elites carried a big chunk of the burden, and that (2) the most influential economic groups agreed on the implementation of the tax.\footnote{See also \textcite{Beramendi2016}.} In fact, \textcite{Bergman2003} explains that Chile is one of the few successful cases of tax compliance in Latin America. 


% motivate models, and remind main conclusions before jumping into the models.
The Chilean case suggests a number of hypotheses. First, there existed a structural economic cleavage between the industrial and agricultural sectors. Second, agricultural political elites implemented policies that played in their own favor. Third, the rise of the industrial class challenged the landowning classes. Fourth, given their similar degree of economic and military resources, both elites compromised the income tax. As explained before, implementing the income tax early had positive consequences to state consolidation. The next section is an attempt to generalize, and test, one particular link of this chain: the rise of the industrial classes, and the early implementation of the income tax. 




