% models
\autoref{results:1} shows 3 models.\footnote{All tables were produced using the  \texttt{texreg} package \autocite[]{Leifeld:2013qr}. All Cox models were computed using the \texttt{survival R}  package (\cite{Therneau:2015zr}). The GEE logistic regression was computed using the \texttt{geepack} package \autocite[]{Hojsgaard:2016}. The simulations were performed using the \texttt{simPH R} package (\cite{Gandrud2015}).} Following \textcite{Aidt2009a}, Model 1 computes the lagged conditional hazard ratio of a country which has not yet adopted the income tax, adopts it in a given year, as a function of industrial and agricultural outputs.\footnote{Following \textcite[49]{Box-Steffensmeier2004}, the next equation was fitted: 
\begin{equation}\label{cox:eq}
h_{i}(t) = exp(\beta_{1}\text{Industrial Growth}_{i,t-1} + \beta_{2}\text{Agricultural Growth}_{i,t-1} + \beta_{3}\text{Total Population}_{i,t-1})h_{0}(t)
\end{equation}
for all countries $i$ and years $t$.} Countries drop out of the sample when they adopt the income tax. Lagging the independent variables should account for non-contemporaneous factors that might conflate the contribution of sectoral growths, such as prior state capacities, among others. Model 2 shows the estimated coefficients of a generalized estimating equation (GEE).\footnote{Following \textcite[331]{Zorn2006}, the next equation was fitted:
\begin{equation}\label{gee:eq}
\pi_{i,t}=\Phi(\beta_{1}\text{log(Industrial Growth$_{i,t}$)}+\beta_{2}\text{log(Agricultural Growth$_{i,t}$)}+\beta_{3}\text{log(Total Population$_{i,t}$)})
\end{equation}
where $\pi$ is the logit link function, and $\Phi$ is as scale parameter (i.e. the cumulative distribution function), for all $i$ countries, and years $t$.} Generalized estimating equations were introduced by \textcite{Liang1986} to fit clustered, repeated/correlated, and panel data \autocite[322]{Zorn2006}. This method is especially well suited to analyze binary data \parencite{Hanley2003a}, something particularly useful given the nature of the dependent variable (e.g. whether a polity has implemented the income tax or not). GEE methods require analysts to parameterize the working correlation matrix. Though \textcite[139]{Hedeker2006} explain that ``the GEE is robust to misspecification of the correlation structure,''\footnote{\textcite[402]{Carlin2001} argue that ``[r]elatively minor differences in estimates may arise depending on how the estimating equations are weighted, in particular within the generalized estimating equation (GEE) framework.'' \textcite[]{Westgate2017a} and \textcite[227]{Gardiner2009} make the same point.} \textcite[338]{Zorn2006} explains that whereas the choice of estimator makes little or no difference, the unit on which the data are grouped makes a big difference. Hence, following the advice of \textcite[166]{Hardin2013}, who point out that when ``the observations are clustered (not collected over time) [...] the exchangeable correlation structure'' should be used, I assume an ``independence'' working covariance structure, which also corrects for small-sized panel designs.\footnote{\textcite[166]{Hardin2013} explains that if ``the number of panels is small, then the independence model may be the best; but [analysts should] calculate the sandwich estimate of variance for use with hypothesis tests and interpretation of coefficient,'' which is what I report in \autoref{results:1}.} Substantively, GEE models provide an estimated marginal mean, or the \emph{weighted average} of all cluster-specific effects (or conditional means). Model 3 is a conditional logit model (``fixed effects'').\footnote{More formally,
\begin{equation}\label{clogit:eq}
\pi_{i,t}=\Phi(\beta_{0} + \beta_{1}\text{log(Industrial Growth$_{i,t}$)}+\beta_{2}\text{log(Agricultural Growth$_{i,t}$)}+\beta_{3}\text{log(Total Population$_{i,t}$)}+\alpha_{i})
\end{equation}
where $\alpha$ are the country fixed effects for all countries $i$.} One important advantage of this strategy is the ability to account for country-specific effects. For example, fiscal expansion could be a function of country-specific prior state-building capacities.\footnote{I thank Matthias vom Hau for this suggestion.} A number of scholars rightly argue that post-colonial state-capacities are in part a function of pre-colonial state-capacities (\cite[1416]{Wimmer2016}, \cite{Mahoney:2010aa}, \cite[1426]{Lange2006}). Fixed-effects should be able to account for these and other unobserved or hard-to-measure covariates, which if left unaccounted for, would introduce omitted variable biases \parencite{Angrist:2008fk}. \autoref{results:2} in the Online Appendix section shows other models, including one with a different transformation to capture different shapes of the baseline hazard, and another one to account for possible spatial dependency. The results do not vary. All models suggest that the rise of a strong industrial sector largely accelerates the implementation of the income tax law. Moreover, a strong agricultural sector not only has zero impact on fiscal development, but a negative one. 



