\subsection{Alternative Models: Lagged-logged Independent Variables and Spatial Dependency}

Model 1 is a Cox regression, but with lagged logged variables. By including time-transformed variables, in the form of a lagged independent variable---to account for partial adjustment of behavior \parencite{Wawro2002}---it is possible ``the use of the natural log transformation [to capture] different forms (or ``shapes'') of the baseline hazard'' \parencite[75]{Box-Steffensmeier2004}. Model 2 accounts for possible spatial-temporal dependence.\footnote{I thank both Christopher Zorn and David Darmofal for this suggestion.} Given that most countries in the sample are contiguous neighbors, it is reasonable to expect a ``domino'' effect.\footnote{For a more detailed spatial take on fiscal expansion, see \textcite{Thies2016}.} Theoretically, being the first country in implementing the income tax might not require the same level of domestic ``effort'' as being the last one. Early-implementers might not have prior experience, making it harder for them to pass the law. To account for this possible spatial-temporal dependence, a cumulative count of countries which have implemented the law at time $t$ was included.\footnote{I clustered the standard errors at the counting variable level. Clustering by the counting variable allows me to cluster by early or late implementers.} 


